WEBVTT

NOTE
Draft captions matching the conversational narration in demo-script.md /
demo-transcript.md (and the read-off FINAL-SCRIPT.md). Cue times follow the
script's timing budget (target ~7:15). Before acceptance, reconcile them against
what is actually said on the recording; captions never override the real
narration. Synthetic MVP — no customer data.

1
00:00.000 --> 00:04.000
Synthetic MVP — no customer data.

2
00:04.000 --> 00:12.000
Hey — I'm Varun. I built this thing called
Mahoraga, let me walk you through it.

3
00:12.000 --> 00:20.000
Short version: it's a memory engine
for offensive security.

4
00:20.000 --> 00:30.000
I built it as one small service — Java, Postgres,
a real transactional ingestion path —

5
00:30.000 --> 00:40.000
plus deterministic synthetic fixtures. No LLM in
the core, so it comes out identical every run.

6
00:40.000 --> 00:48.000
First — and I'll keep saying this —
everything here is fake data.

7
00:48.000 --> 00:56.000
A swarm attacks a customer, finds a bunch
of stuff, writes it down...

8
00:56.000 --> 01:03.000
then the engagement ends
and it throws the notebook away.

9
01:03.000 --> 01:10.000
Next quarter it starts from zero.
That's what I'm fixing — the memory.

10
01:10.000 --> 01:18.000
One command does the whole thing.
Preflight is just me being careful —

11
01:18.000 --> 01:26.000
it checks Java, Docker, the build,
the guards, and changes nothing.

12
01:26.000 --> 01:35.000
It loads Engagement 1, then draws a hard line:
everything we knew, as of right now.

13
01:35.000 --> 01:44.000
Storing stuff is fine — does the memory
change what you do next?

14
01:44.000 --> 01:53.000
The planner runs at that Engagement 1 line,
before we know round two.

15
01:53.000 --> 02:02.000
And this is what people get wrong:
it's so easy to let the future leak in.

16
02:02.000 --> 02:11.000
So the planner only ever sees opaque IDs.
No labels, no results.

17
02:11.000 --> 02:20.000
Memory off, it goes in order: A, B, C.

18
02:20.000 --> 02:31.000
Memory on, it knows one got fixed last time
and pulls it to the front: C, A, B.

19
02:31.000 --> 02:41.000
Both plans actually run — same starting point,
same outcomes baked in.

20
02:41.000 --> 02:50.000
The bug that came back? Memory catches it first,
not third. Three to one. Nothing leaked.

21
02:50.000 --> 02:59.000
Between the two engagements the pod got
a new ID, a new name, a new IP —

22
02:59.000 --> 03:08.000
everything you'd key on changed. But the
Deployment underneath is the same.

23
03:08.000 --> 03:17.000
So we keep it as the same asset,
and the finding stays stuck to it.

24
03:17.000 --> 03:27.000
Opposite case: something genuinely fuzzy,
a reused DNS name with nothing behind it.

25
03:27.000 --> 03:34.000
It doesn't guess — it marks it ambiguous
and won't let it move any numbers.

26
03:34.000 --> 03:40.000
It'd rather say "I don't know" than merge
two things that might not match.

27
03:40.000 --> 03:49.000
Same exact Engagement 2 facts —
I'm not touching the data.

28
03:49.000 --> 03:58.000
I'm just changing how much history
it's allowed to look at.

29
03:58.000 --> 04:08.000
No memory, a normal scan: three detections,
one not-detected, one partial.

30
04:08.000 --> 04:18.000
And the finding nobody retested? It just isn't
there. The scan can't even see it.

31
04:18.000 --> 04:28.000
Turn history back on, same facts,
and suddenly they mean something.

32
04:28.000 --> 04:38.000
New, still open, verified fixed, regressed,
not retested, inconclusive.

33
04:38.000 --> 04:48.000
"Verified fixed" only counts if we reran
the same check and it came back clean.

34
04:48.000 --> 04:57.000
Not seeing a bug is not the same
as the bug being gone.

35
04:57.000 --> 05:05.000
Only memory can tell you a fix came back,
or that you forgot to retest something.

36
05:05.000 --> 05:14.000
This is the unglamorous stuff
that just has to work.

37
05:14.000 --> 05:23.000
Same event twice — no-op.
A conflicting one — rejected.

38
05:23.000 --> 05:32.000
Ask for a report before the data's complete —
it blocks you.

39
05:32.000 --> 05:41.000
Shuffle the arrival order — same report.
Kill a transaction halfway — nothing left behind.

40
05:41.000 --> 05:50.000
Same facts, same answer, every time.
That's what you have to trust first.

41
05:50.000 --> 06:00.000
So why did I actually build this?
Honestly, mostly for fun.

42
06:00.000 --> 06:10.000
Armadin's probably already on this — but I think
there's real power in memory for security.

43
06:10.000 --> 06:20.000
There's more I'd do. Integration: I found an
open-source project called T3MP3ST —

44
06:20.000 --> 06:30.000
a multi-agent offensive framework that runs the
whole kill chain, but has no memory.

45
06:30.000 --> 06:38.000
Bolting Mahoraga onto something like that
would be a super natural fit.

46
06:38.000 --> 06:48.000
Architecture: split the memory flow into pieces —
a writer, a reader, a report job, a shared core.

47
06:48.000 --> 06:58.000
Plus topology drift, tradecraft memory, hash-chained
provenance, and sharing learnings across customers.

48
06:58.000 --> 07:05.000
Each is its own project. But the core —
the memory engine — that's what's proven here.

49
07:05.000 --> 07:14.000
Everything you saw — the 3-to-1, identity, the six
categories, the correctness checks —

50
07:14.000 --> 07:21.000
none of it is hardcoded. It's computed from
the actual run, identical every time.

51
07:21.000 --> 07:25.000
Fake data, yeah. But a real result.
Thanks for watching.
